00:10:56,238 --> 00:10:57,657
I have big news.

102
00:11:01,035 --> 00:11:02,411
What's the big news?

103
00:11:05,915 --> 00:11:07,249
What is it?

104
00:11:09,752 --> 00:11:10,795
What is it about?

105
00:11:20,513 --> 00:11:21,639
My gosh, it's Dr. Cha!

106
00:11:22,431 --> 00:11:23,766
-What?
-My gosh, seriously.

107
00:11:24,975 --> 00:11:26,727
-What is it?
-It's about Dr. Cha.

108
00:11:28,104 --> 00:11:30,189
DR. CHA'S NEW CHALLENGE,

109
00:11:30,272 --> 00:11:32,316
"Dr. Cha, who's known to have
a mutated version

110
00:11:32,400 --> 00:11:34,860
of the ntrk1 gene which is
the cause of CIPA,

111
00:11:34,944 --> 00:11:37,071
joined the medical research team

112
00:11:37,154 --> 00:11:39,240
and helped accelerate
the research of medication

113
00:11:39,323 --> 00:11:41,826
that's been showing strong signs
of pain-relieving effects."

114
00:11:42,743 --> 00:11:45,871
I guess Dr. Cha is doing very well.

115
00:11:46,580 --> 00:11:50,459
Judging by how much
he's achieved in just one year,

116
00:11:50,543 --> 00:11:53,379
it's pretty obvious
that he must be really busy.

117
00:11:53,462 --> 00:11:55,798
Yes, you're right.
No wonder he's been out of touch.

118
00:11:55,881 --> 00:11:57,550
-Yes, of course.
-Let me see him again.

119
00:11:59,760 --> 00:12:03,431
Dr. Cha has lost so much weight.

120
00:12:03,514 --> 00:12:04,765
You're right.

121
00:12:04,849 --> 00:12:07,309
He's participating
both as a patient and a researcher.

122
00:12:07,393 --> 00:12:09,937
So he's probably twice as busy.

123
00:12:14,442 --> 00:12:16,402
Let's go have a drink.

124
00:12:16,485 --> 00:12:18,279
-Yes, let's go have a drink.
-Okay.

125
00:12:18,362 --> 00:12:21,282
-Let's go. Where should we go?
-Come on.

126
00:12:42,511 --> 00:12:45,389
Dr. Kang, you should understand him.

127
00:12:46,098 --> 00:12:48,434
Guys have trouble
doing multiple things at once.

128
00:12:48,517 --> 00:12:50,352
He's right.

129
00:12:50,436 --> 00:12:52,605
On top of that,
he's working on a huge project.

130
00:12:52,688 --> 00:12:55,441
-It won't be easy for him to contact you.
-Yes, of course.

131
00:12:55,524 --> 00:12:58,277
-That's practically impossible.
-Exactly.

132
00:12:59,612 --> 00:13:00,488
That's enough.

133
00:13:00,571 --> 00:13:02,740
Don't stop me.

134
00:13:15,878 --> 00:13:18,506
I personally think men and women

135
00:13:18,589 --> 00:13:21,592
need to be like cats
when it comes to love.

136
00:13:22,176 --> 00:13:24,970
Cats know how to make you feel desperate.

137
00:13:25,054 --> 00:13:27,640
They're different from puppies
who are always just focused on you.

138
00:13:27,723 --> 00:13:29,391
Are you calling my sister a puppy?

139
00:13:29,475 --> 00:13:31,519
Did you just compare her to a dog?

140
00:13:31,602 --> 00:13:34,021
-No, that's not what I meant.
-Are you saying she's wrong

141
00:13:34,104 --> 00:13:37,191
-for giving him unconditional attention?
-Why are you taking it out on me?

142
00:13:37,274 --> 00:13:39,777
-I like puppies too.
-Forget it.

143
00:13:39,860 --> 00:13:42,404
I don't want to hear
another word from you men.

144
00:13:42,488 --> 00:13:44,073
Let's drink, Si-young.

145
00:14:05,511 --> 00:14:09,890
I guess I'll never be number one

146
00:14:09,974 --> 00:14:13,143
to Dr. Cha.

147
00:14:14,019 --> 00:14:18,023
Stop crying. Don't cry.

148
00:14:19,233 --> 00:14:22,570
His patients always came first.

149
00:14:22,653 --> 00:14:25,573
And now, he's more focused
on his research.

150
00:14:29,076 --> 00:14:30,035
That mean jerk.

151
00:14:31,161 --> 00:14:35,416
Yes, he's a mean jerk. What a mean jerk.

152
00:14:40,004 --> 00:14:41,714
Don't cry.

153
00:14:42,923 --> 00:14:44,842
Si-young, just forget about him.

154
00:14:45,718 --> 00:14:48,304
How can I forget about him?

155
00:14:49,054 --> 00:14:50,764
I can't forget about him.

156
00:15:19,793 --> 00:15:21,795
Si-young, let's go.

157
00:16:31,281 --> 00:16:35,828
3 YEARS LATER

158
00:16:39,498 --> 00:16:41,792
"Suspected to have acute appendicitis."

159
00:16:43,627 --> 00:16:44,586
Who did this?

160
00:16:47,631 --> 00:16:48,507
Me.

161
00:16:50,092 --> 00:16:51,260
You tried your best.

162
00:16:54,638 --> 00:16:57,599
You should either be able
to diagnose or treat a patient.

163
00:16:57,683 --> 00:16:59,643
At least have some experience
for goodness' sake.

164
00:16:59,727 --> 00:17:01,395
You're a second-year resident.

165
00:17:01,478 --> 00:17:03,605
The best you could think
of was acute appendicitis?

166
00:17:03,689 --> 00:17:06,275
I told you that you're not
in school anymore.

167
00:17:06,358 --> 00:17:08,152
The patients aren't here
so you could practice.

168
00:17:08,235 --> 00:17:10,320
"You did a great job for a resident."

169
00:17:10,404 --> 00:17:13,657
If that's the kind of compliment
you want to hear,

170
00:17:13,741 --> 00:17:14,783
just go back to school!

171
00:17:14,867 --> 00:17:15,993
Respond to her.

172
00:17:16,076 --> 00:17:16,994
We'll try harder!

173
00:17:17,077 --> 00:17:19,163
This is so frustrating!

174
00:17:19,246 --> 00:17:21,665
You guys are unbelievable.
Get out of my way.

175
00:17:26,879 --> 00:17:30,007
Hey. What was her nickname again?

176
00:17:31,341 --> 00:17:33,302
-Crazy Kang.
-"Crazy Kang"?

177
00:17:34,053 --> 00:17:35,345
Crazy Kang Si-young.

178
00:17:57,201 --> 00:17:58,619
Excuse me.

179
00:19:28,333 --> 00:19:29,543
It's been a while.

180
00:19:42,431 --> 00:19:43,390
Have you been well?

181
00:19:47,936 --> 00:19:49,062
Yes.

182
00:19:57,696 --> 00:20:00,407
ANESTHESIOLOGIST KANG SI-YOUNG

183
00:20:01,241 --> 00:20:02,659
Are you a first-year fellow now?

184
00:20:04,661 --> 00:20:05,829
Yes.

185
00:20:11,210 --> 00:20:12,252
Congratulations.

186
00:20:13,337 --> 00:20:15,255
I saw your research results.

187
00:20:15,339 --> 00:20:17,466
It passed the first round
of clinical trials, right?

188
00:20:18,175 --> 00:20:19,092
Thanks.

189
00:20:21,011 --> 00:20:22,304
How is your health?

190
00:20:23,847 --> 00:20:25,098
It's become a lot better.

191
00:20:26,767 --> 00:20:27,809
I'm fine now.

192
00:20:31,855 --> 00:20:33,148
I'm relieved.

193
00:20:35,359 --> 00:20:36,735
When did you get back to Korea?

194
00:20:37,486 --> 00:20:38,570
About a year ago.

195
00:20:44,743 --> 00:20:45,994
Why are you here, by the way?

196
00:20:55,879 --> 00:20:58,006
What are you doing here at this hospital?

197
00:21:06,598 --> 00:21:07,808
Hello?

198
00:21:10,310 --> 00:21:12,145
Okay. I'll be right there.

199
00:21:15,440 --> 00:21:18,193
I have to go see a patient.

200
00:21:19,403 --> 00:21:20,654
Sure, go ahead.

201
00:22:33,477 --> 00:22:35,437
HOSPICE AND PALLIATIVE CARE CENTER
MANAGEMENT PLANS

202
00:22:35,520 --> 00:22:37,147
OBJECTIVES AND SIGNIFICANCE OF THE CENTER

203
00:22:37,230 --> 00:22:39,858
-Hospice care?
-Yes.

204
00:22:40,734 --> 00:22:43,362
We have only 20 beds
for hospice care at the moment.

205
00:22:43,445 --> 00:22:46,239
I'd like to expand it
into a hospice and palliative care center

206
00:22:46,323 --> 00:22:47,449
for terminal patients.

207
00:22:47,532 --> 00:22:50,327
Terminal patients cannot be cured.
We can only sustain their state.

208
00:22:50,410 --> 00:22:52,079
And?

209
00:22:52,162 --> 00:22:54,456
We're not a nursing hospital.

210
00:22:54,539 --> 00:22:55,999
It won't help the finances either.

211
00:22:56,083 --> 00:23:00,337
Do we really need to provide
hospice care for terminal patients?

212
00:23:00,420 --> 00:23:04,966
Our goal as doctors and as a hospital
should not just be to cure diseases.

213
00:23:05,050 --> 00:23:07,677
We should try to improve the quality
of life of our patients as well.

214
00:23:07,761 --> 00:23:11,848
Death does not happen in a moment.
It is a process.

215
00:23:13,100 --> 00:23:15,727
It is also our task

216
00:23:15,811 --> 00:23:18,146
to help patients in their dying process.

217
00:23:20,816 --> 00:23:24,403
I completely agree with Chairwoman Min.

218
00:23:25,028 --> 00:23:27,697
So far, we've been sending
patients home when we feel

219
00:23:27,781 --> 00:23:29,658
there's nothing more we can do.

220
00:23:29,741 --> 00:23:33,412
Now we'll be able to feel less guilty.

221
00:23:37,999 --> 00:23:39,543
I think it's a good idea.

222
00:23:39,626 --> 00:23:42,254
It's a difficult
and unprofitable business.

223
00:23:42,337 --> 00:23:43,630
Why is she pushing ahead with it?

224
00:23:43,713 --> 00:23:45,173
Exactly.

225
00:23:45,257 --> 00:23:48,385
Chairwoman Min tends to be too reckless.

226
00:23:54,307 --> 00:23:56,852
Tae-kyung, Dr. Cha is here.

227
00:23:56,935 --> 00:23:59,896
-Is he? Tell him to come see me.
-Okay.

228
00:24:08,655 --> 00:24:09,781
What's wrong?

229
00:24:12,659 --> 00:24:13,618
I'm sorry I'm late.

230
00:24:15,412 --> 00:24:16,371
What's the problem?

231
00:24:16,455 --> 00:24:19,416
She was treated by me, and she's
suddenly having bad abdominal pain.

232
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:21,376
Analgesics won't work.

233
00:24:28,133 --> 00:24:29,259
The pain is gone now.

234
00:24:30,385 --> 00:24:32,095
-Pardon?
-Why?

235
00:24:35,348 --> 00:24:37,058
Are you okay now?

236
00:24:37,726 --> 00:24:39,936
Yes. Didn't I tell you?

237
00:24:40,020 --> 00:24:43,190
One moment the pain is killing me,
the next I'm fine.

238
00:24:48,028 --> 00:24:51,031
Big news! You're not going to believe it!

239
00:24:56,703 --> 00:24:57,621
Sorry.

240
00:25:00,415 --> 00:25:04,461
Dr. Lee. There's no family history
of convulsive disease.

241
00:25:04,544 --> 00:25:06,922
Her echocardiogram,
lung and abdomen X-rays,

242
00:25:07,005 --> 00:25:08,965
and CT scans show no abnormalities either.

243
00:25:09,049 --> 00:25:10,300
-Well…
-We're doing

244
00:25:10,383 --> 00:25:12,719
a gastroscopy and a colonoscopy
this afternoon.

245
00:25:12,802 --> 00:25:15,388
As we found no abnormalities last time,

246
00:25:15,472 --> 00:25:19,017
we'll do a fecal immunochemical test
and also a stool culture this time.

247
00:25:19,100 --> 00:25:21,937
What is it, Dr. Heo?
What have you been trying to say?

248
00:25:22,479 --> 00:25:25,440
The thing is, Dr. Cha is
in our hospital right now.

249
00:25:27,859 --> 00:25:29,778
Dr. Cha? Right now?

250
00:25:29,861 --> 00:25:32,364
Yes. Someone saw him.

251
00:25:33,114 --> 00:25:35,700
Unbelievable.
When did he get back from the US?

252
00:25:35,784 --> 00:25:37,953
Will he work here again?

253
00:25:38,036 --> 00:25:41,206
I'm not sure about that.
But from what I heard, he looks amazing.

254
00:25:41,289 --> 00:25:44,125
He was always handsome,
but he's become a lot fitter now.

255
00:25:44,209 --> 00:25:46,586
Anyway,
he looks absolutely charismatic now.

256
00:25:46,670 --> 00:25:48,255
I'm not even surprised.

257
